# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: camakau
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:camakau/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:camakau/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:camakau/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:camakau/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:camakau/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:camakau/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:camakau/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:camakau/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:camakau/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:camakau/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:camakau/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:camakau/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:camakau/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:camakau/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:camakau/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:camakau/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:camakau/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:camakau/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:camakau/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:camakau/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:camakau/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:camakau/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:camakau/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:camakau/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:camakau/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:camakau/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:camakau/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:camakau/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:camakau/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The **Austronesian languages** (/ˌɔːstrəˈniːʒən/ *AW-strə-NEE-zhən*) are a language family widely spoken throughout Maritime Southeast Asia, parts of Mainland Southeast Asia, Madagascar, the islands of the Pacific Ocean and Taiwan (by Taiwanese indigenous peoples).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] They are spoken by about 386 million people (4.4% of the world population).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This makes it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (one variant standardized as Indonesian), Javanese, Sundanese, Tagalog (standardized as Filipino), Malagasy and Cebuano.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] According to some estimates, the family contains 1,257 languages, which is the second most of any language family.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] In 1706, the Dutch scholar Adriaan Reland first observed similarities between the languages spoken in the South East Asia Archipelago and by peoples on islands in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Wilhelm von Humboldt, Herman van der Tuuk) started to apply the comparative method to the Austronesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The first extensive study on the history of the phonology was made by the German linguist Otto Dempwolff.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] It included a reconstruction of the Proto-Austronesian lexicon.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The term *Austronesian* was coined (as German **austronesisch**) by Wilhelm Schmidt, deriving it from Latin **auster** "south" and Ancient Greek *νῆσος* (*nêsos* "island"), meaning the "Southern Island languages".
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Most Austronesian languages are spoken by the people of Insular Southeast Asia and Oceania.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Only a few languages, such as Peninsular Malay varieties, Jakun, Temuan, Urak Lawoiʼ and the Chamic languages (except Acehnese), are indigenous to mainland Asia, or Malagasy which is the only Austronesian language indigenous to Insular East Africa.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] There are few Austronesian languages which have populations exceeding a few thousand, but a handful have speaking populations in the millions; Indonesian, the most widely spoken, has around 252 million speakers, making it the tenth most-spoken language in the world.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Approximately twenty Austronesian languages are official in their respective countries.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] By the number of languages they include, Austronesian and Niger–Congo are the two largest language families in the world.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] They each contain roughly one-fifth of the world's languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The geographical span of Austronesian was the largest of any language family in the first half of the second millennium CE, before the spread of Indo-European languages in the colonial period.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] It ranges from Madagascar to Easter Island in the eastern Pacific.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] According to Robert Blust (1999), Austronesian is divided into several primary branches, all but one of which are found exclusively in Taiwan.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Formosan languages of Taiwan are grouped into as many as nine first-order subgroups of Austronesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] All Austronesian languages spoken outside the Taiwan mainland (including its offshore Yami language) belong to the Malayo-Polynesian (sometimes called *Extra-Formosan*) branch.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Most Austronesian languages lack a long history of written attestation.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The oldest inscription in the Cham language, the Đông Yên Châu inscription dated to c.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] 350 AD, is the first attestation of any Austronesian language.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Austronesian languages overall possess phoneme inventories which are smaller than the world average.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Around 90% of the Austronesian languages have inventories of 19–25 sounds (15–20 consonants and 4–5 vowels), thus lying at the lower end of the global typical range of 20–37 sounds.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] However, extreme inventories are also found, such as Nemi (New Caledonia) with 43 consonants.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The canonical root type in Proto-Austronesian is disyllabic with the shape CV(C)CVC (C = consonant; V = vowel), and is still found in many Austronesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] In most languages, consonant clusters are only allowed in medial position, and often, there are restrictions for the first element of the cluster.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] There is a common drift to reduce the number of consonants which can appear in final position, e.g.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Buginese, which only allows the two consonants /ŋ/ and /ʔ/ as finals, out of a total number of 18 consonants.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Complete absence of final consonants is observed e.g. in Nias, Malagasy and many Oceanic languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Tonal contrasts are rare in Austronesian languages, although Moken–Moklen and a few languages of the Chamic, South Halmahera–West New Guinea and New Caledonian subgroups do show lexical tone.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Most Austronesian languages are agglutinative languages with a relatively high number of affixes, and clear morpheme boundaries.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Most affixes are prefixes (Malay *ber-jalan* 'walk' < *jalan* 'road'), with a smaller number of suffixes (Tagalog *titis-án* 'ashtray' < *títis* 'ash') and infixes (Roviana *t<in>avete* 'work (noun)' < *tavete* 'work (verb)').
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Reduplication is commonly employed in Austronesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This includes full reduplication (Malay *anak-anak* 'children' < *anak* 'child'; Karo Batak *nipe-nipe* 'caterpillar' < *nipe* 'snake') or partial reduplication (Agta *taktakki* 'legs' < *takki* 'leg', *at-atu* 'puppy' < *atu* 'dog').
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] It is difficult to make generalizations about the languages that make up a family as diverse as Austronesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The word for *eye* in many Austronesian languages is *mata* (from the most northerly Austronesian languages, Formosan languages such as Bunun and Amis all the way south to Māori).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The word for *two* is also stable, in that it appears over the entire range of the Austronesian family, but the forms (e.g.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Bunun *dusa*; Amis *tusa*; Māori *rua*) require some linguistic expertise to recognise.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Austronesian Basic Vocabulary Database gives word lists (coded for cognateness) for approximately 1000 Austronesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The internal structure of the Austronesian languages is complex.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The family consists of many similar and closely related languages with large numbers of dialect continua, making it difficult to recognize boundaries between branches.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The first major step towards high-order subgrouping was Dempwolff's recognition of the Oceanic subgroup (called *Melanesisch* by Dempwolff).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The special position of the languages of Taiwan was first recognized by André-Georges Haudricourt (1965), who divided the Austronesian languages into three subgroups: Northern Austronesian (= Formosan), Eastern Austronesian (= Oceanic), and Western Austronesian (all remaining languages).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] In a study that represents the first lexicostatistical classification of the Austronesian languages, Isidore Dyen (1965) presented a radically different subgrouping scheme.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] He posited 40 first-order subgroups, with the highest degree of diversity found in the area of Melanesia.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Oceanic languages are not recognized, but are distributed over more than 30 of his proposed first-order subgroups.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Dyen's classification was widely criticized and for the most part rejected, but several of his lower-order subgroups are still accepted (e.g. the Cordilleran languages, the Bilic languages or the Murutic languages).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Subsequently, the position of the Formosan languages as the most archaic group of Austronesian languages was recognized by Otto Christian Dahl (1973), followed by proposals from other scholars that the Formosan languages actually make up more than one first-order subgroup of Austronesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Robert Blust (1977) first presented the subgrouping model which is currently accepted by virtually all scholars in the field, with more than one first-order subgroup on Taiwan, and a single first-order branch encompassing all Austronesian languages spoken outside of Taiwan, viz.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The relationships of the Formosan languages to each other and the internal structure of Malayo-Polynesian continue to be debated.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] In addition to Malayo-Polynesian, thirteen Formosan subgroups are broadly accepted.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The seminal article in the classification of Formosan—and, by extension, the top-level structure of Austronesian—is Blust (1999).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Prominent Formosanists (linguists who specialize in Formosan languages) take issue with some of its details, but it remains the point of reference for current linguistic analyses.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Debate centers primarily around the relationships between these families.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Of the classifications presented here, Blust (1999) links two families into a Western Plains group, two more in a Northwestern Formosan group, and three into an Eastern Formosan group, while Li (2008) also links five families into a Northern Formosan group.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Harvey (1982), Chang (2006) and Ross (2012) split Tsouic, and Blust (2013) agrees the group is probably not valid.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Other studies have presented phonological evidence for a reduced Paiwanic family of Paiwanic, Puyuma, Bunun, Amis, and Malayo-Polynesian, but this is not reflected in vocabulary.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Eastern Formosan peoples Basay, Kavalan, and Amis share a homeland motif that has them coming originally from an island called *Sinasay* or *Sanasay*.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Amis, in particular, maintain that they came from the east, and were treated by the Puyuma, amongst whom they settled, as a subservient group.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This classification retains Blust's East Formosan, and unites the other northern languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Li (2008) proposes a Proto-Formosan (F0) ancestor and equates it with Proto-Austronesian (PAN), following the model in Starosta (1995).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Rukai and Tsouic are seen as highly divergent, although the position of Rukai is highly controversial.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Sagart (2021) finds other shared innovations that follow the same pattern.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The fact that the Kradai languages share the numeral system (and other lexical innovations) of pMP suggests that they are a coordinate branch with Malayo-Polynesian, rather than a sister family to Austronesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The Malayo-Polynesian languages are—among other things—characterized by certain sound changes, such as the mergers of Proto-Austronesian (PAN) *t/*C to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian (PMP) *t, and PAN *n/*N to PMP *n, and the shift of PAN *S to PMP *h.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] There appear to have been two great migrations of Austronesian languages that quickly covered large areas, resulting in multiple local groups with little large-scale structure.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The first was Malayo-Polynesian, distributed across the Malay archipelago and Melanesia.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The second migration was that of the Oceanic languages into Polynesia and Micronesia.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] According to Robert Blust, the Formosan languages form nine of the ten primary branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] At least since Sapir (1968), writing in 1949, linguists have generally accepted that the chronology of the dispersal of languages within a given language family can be traced from the area of greatest linguistic variety to that of the least.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] For example, English in North America has large numbers of speakers, but relatively low dialectal diversity, while English in Great Britain has much higher diversity; such low linguistic variety by Sapir's thesis suggests a more recent spread of English in North America.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] While some scholars suspect that the number of principal branches among the Formosan languages may be somewhat less than Blust's estimate of nine (e.g.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Li 2006), there is little contention among linguists with this analysis and the resulting view of the origin and direction of the migration.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] For a recent dissenting analysis, see Peiros (2004).
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The protohistory of the Austronesian people can be traced farther back through time.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] To get an idea of the original homeland of the populations ancestral to the Austronesian peoples (as opposed to strictly linguistic arguments), evidence from archaeology and population genetics may be adduced.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Studies from the science of genetics have produced conflicting outcomes.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Some researchers find evidence for a proto-Austronesian homeland on the Asian mainland (e.g., Melton et al.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] 1998), while others mirror the linguistic research, rejecting an East Asian origin in favor of Taiwan (e.g., Trejaut et al.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Archaeological evidence (e.g., Bellwood 1997) is more consistent, suggesting that the ancestors of the Austronesians spread from the South Chinese mainland to Taiwan at some time around 8,000 years ago.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Evidence from historical linguistics suggests that it is from this island that seafaring peoples migrated, perhaps in distinct waves separated by millennia, to the entire region encompassed by the Austronesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] It is believed that this migration began around 6,000 years ago.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] However, evidence from historical linguistics cannot bridge the gap between those two periods.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The view that linguistic evidence connects Austronesian languages to the Sino-Tibetan ones, as proposed for example by Sagart (2002), is a minority one.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Linguistic analysis of the Proto-Austronesian language stops at the western shores of Taiwan; any related mainland language(s) have not survived.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The only exceptions, the Chamic languages, derive from more recent migration to the mainland.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] However, according to Ostapirat's interpretation of the seriously discussed Austro-Tai hypothesis, the Kra–Dai languages (also known as Tai–Kadai) are exactly those related mainland languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Genealogical links have been proposed between Austronesian and various families of East and Southeast Asia.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] An Austro-Tai proposal linking Austronesian and the Kra-Dai languages of the southeastern continental Asian mainland was first proposed by Paul K.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Benedict, and is supported by Weera Ostapirat, Roger Blench, and Laurent Sagart, based on the traditional comparative method.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Ostapirat (2005) proposes a series of regular correspondences linking the two families and assumes a primary split, with Kra-Dai speakers being the people who stayed behind in their Chinese homeland.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Blench (2004) suggests that, if the connection is valid, the relationship is unlikely to be one of two sister families.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Rather, he suggests that proto-Kra-Dai speakers were Austronesians who migrated to Hainan Island and back to the mainland from the northern Philippines, and that their distinctiveness results from radical restructuring following contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] An extended version of Austro-Tai was hypothesized by Benedict who added the Japonic languages to the proposal as well.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] A link with the Austroasiatic languages in an 'Austric' phylum is based mostly on typological evidence.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] However, there is also morphological evidence of a connection between the conservative Nicobarese languages and Austronesian languages of the Philippines.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Robert Blust supports the hypothesis which connects the lower Yangtze neolithic Austro-Tai entity with the rice-cultivating Austro-Asiatic cultures, assuming the center of East Asian rice domestication, and putative Austric homeland, to be located in the Yunnan/Burma border area.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Under that view, there was an east-west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] French linguist and Sinologist Laurent Sagart considers the Austronesian languages to be related to the Sino-Tibetan languages, and also groups the Kra–Dai languages as more closely related to the Malayo-Polynesian languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Sagart argues for a north-south genetic relationship between Chinese and Austronesian, based on sound correspondences in the basic vocabulary and morphological parallels.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Laurent Sagart (2017) concludes that the possession of the two kinds of millets in Taiwanese Austronesian languages (not just Setaria, as previously thought) places the pre-Austronesians in northeastern China, adjacent to the probable Sino-Tibetan homeland.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] (2017) are also in agreement with Sagart's proposal, in which their analyses show that the predominantly Austronesian Y-DNA haplogroup O3a2b*-P164(xM134) belongs to a newly defined haplogroup O3a2b2-N6 being widely distributed along the eastern coastal regions of Asia, from Korea to Vietnam.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Sagart also groups the Austronesian languages in a recursive-like fashion, placing Kra-Dai as a sister branch of Malayo-Polynesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] His methodology has been found to be spurious by his peers.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Several linguists have proposed that Japanese is genetically related to the Austronesian family, cf.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Some other linguists think it is more plausible that Japanese is not genetically related to the Austronesian languages, but instead was influenced by an Austronesian substratum or adstratum.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Those who propose this scenario suggest that the Austronesian family once covered the islands to the north as well as to the south.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Martine Robbeets (2017) claims that Japanese genetically belongs to the "Transeurasian" (= Macro-Altaic) languages, but underwent lexical influence from "para-Austronesian", a presumed sister language of Proto-Austronesian.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The linguist Ann Kumar (2009) proposed that some Austronesians might have migrated to Japan, possibly an elite-group from Java, and created the Japanese-hierarchical society.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] She also identifies 82 possible cognates between Austronesian and Japanese, however her theory remains very controversial.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The linguist Asha Pereltsvaig criticized Kumar's theory on several points.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The archaeological problem with that theory is that, contrary to the claim that there was no rice farming in China and Korea in prehistoric times, excavations have indicated that rice farming has been practiced in this area since at least 5000 BC.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The pre-Yayoi Japanese lineage was not shared with Southeast Asians, but was shared with Northwest Chinese, Tibetans and Central Asians.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Linguistic problems were also pointed out.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Kumar did not claim that Japanese was an Austronesian language derived from proto-Javanese language, but only that it provided a superstratum language for old Japanese, based on 82 plausible Javanese-Japanese cognates, mostly related to rice farming.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] In 2001, Stanley Starosta proposed a new language family named East Asian, that includes all primary language families in the broader East Asia region except Japonic and Koreanic.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This proposed family consists of two branches, Austronesian and Sino-Tibetan-Yangzian, with the Kra-Dai family considered to be a branch of Austronesian, and "Yangzian" to be a new sister branch of Sino-Tibetan consisting of the Austroasiatic and Hmong–Mien languages.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This proposal was further researched by linguists like Michael D.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Larish in 2006, who also included the Japonic and Koreanic languages in the macrofamily.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] The proposal has since been adopted by linguists such as George van Driem, albeit without the inclusion of Japonic and Koreanic.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Blevins (2007) proposed that the Austronesian and the Ongan protolanguage are the descendants of an Austronesian–Ongan protolanguage.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] This view is not supported by mainstream linguists and remains very controversial.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Robert Blust rejects Blevins' proposal as far-fetched and based solely on chance resemblances and methodologically flawed comparisons.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] Most Austronesian languages have Latin-based writing systems today.
[src:camakau/austronesian-language] is used with hundreds and thousands and before qualifiers.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:camakau/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:camakau/camakau] It is theorised that the camakau was invented in the mid-1700s.
[src:camakau/camakau] In the comprehensive research of D'Arcy.
[src:camakau/camakau] C (2014), it is suggested that the main influences in the design of the camakau is Micronesian for the sail rig, particularly via Tonga.
[src:camakau/camakau] There are also Polynesian influences in the design of the canoe.
[src:camakau/camakau] The islands of Lau are located between Fiji and Tonga, and span over 250 nautical islands, meaning that the development of the camakau here was influenced by both of these regions, and the other water vessels of the Lau group.
[src:camakau/camakau] As stated in "Canoes of Oceania", the camakau was particularly used in travelling between islands, and for chiefs of islands to visit each other.
[src:camakau/camakau] These boats were not used for the purpose of war.
[src:camakau/camakau] The use of the camakau declined greatly in the mid-19th century, being replaced by European boats.
[src:camakau/camakau] However, the camakau has been recorded travelling between Fiji and Tonga even in the early 1900s, preferred by traditional users to European cutter.
[src:camakau/camakau] Camakaus are still used in the traditional region today, particularly in the islands in the Lau group.
[src:camakau/camakau] The camakau is culturally perceived as old fashioned when used today, however, economic and environmental reasons make the camakau a very effective alternative to motorboats.
[src:camakau/camakau] The effects of climate change are being particularly felt by Fiji and the surrounding islands due to changing weather patterns as well as rising sea levels, and the associated economic impact of this.
[src:camakau/camakau] Thus, the camakau is being implemented back into society due to its environmental and economic benefits.
[src:camakau/camakau] B (2010) states that modern camakaus' are also implementing nails, marine glue, rope and Styrofoam, taking the traditional design and making it more effective to be used in modern society.
[src:camakau/camakau] The camakau is being used in islands where transportation is difficult, particularly due to the price of fuel and motorboats.
[src:camakau/camakau] The Uto Ni Yalo Trust is an organisation which gifts traditional Fijian canoes to island communities.
[src:camakau/camakau] Further, it has been said that in this community, the boats will help with sustainable fishing practices, as the islanders search for food to feed their family, opposed to fishing in abundance so that they are able to sell them at the market, to be able to afford fish.
[src:camakau/camakau] When building the camakau today, there is an issue of sourcing the wood.
[src:camakau/camakau] This is because the vesi timber, or *Intsia bijuga,* is no longer in abundance.
[src:camakau/camakau] There is a commercial production of wooden bowls made from this wood, which is affecting the supply of wood available for canoe building.
[src:camakau/camakau] Further the economic and social difficulties currently being felt in the Fijian region will place pressure on the ability of the society to reasonably fund and create these canoes.
[src:camakau/camakau] There is growing tourism in Fiji for these traditional canoes to be seen in museums, and on the water as well as for models of the canoes in many countries, including New Zealand.
[src:camakau/camakau] The defining features of the camakau is that it is a single hulled canoe, with a small outrigger boom, and a cama, a float.
[src:camakau/camakau] The camakau is occasionally made in two pieces, in which case it is called a veikoso.
[src:camakau/camakau] An outrigger is a long piece of wood, approximately the length of canoe, attached and parallel to the canoe.
[src:camakau/camakau] The object of the outrigger is to prevent the canoe from upsetting.
[src:camakau/camakau] This canoe has no mast or sail in some of traditional designs which have been excavated by archeologists.
[src:camakau/camakau] The hull is a dugout log, usually a single trunk, but in the case of larger vessels could be two trunks joined together.
[src:camakau/camakau] The design is very similar to the drua, although the drua is double hulled.
[src:camakau/camakau] Fijian canoes have been recorded to be between 55 ft and 70 ft in length, making the camakau able to sail in open ocean, and even travel between Fiji and Tonga.
[src:camakau/camakau] The rig of the camakau, from its Polynesian origins, has a narrower tack angle, and a lower yard.
[src:camakau/camakau] Local materials of the Lau island group, where these canoes have been mostly found to be built, are used in the construction of the canoe.
[src:camakau/camakau] The hard wood *Intsia bijuga* is used to construct the hull as well as masthead, mast step, and steering oar, where durability is most necessary.
[src:camakau/camakau] This wood is also called greenhart or vesi, which grow in rocky areas.
[src:camakau/camakau] There are other very important components to the design of the canoe.
[src:camakau/camakau] Two types of cordage are used, sennit and rigging rope.
[src:camakau/camakau] Sennit, made from the mesocarp of the coconut fruit, is used for lashing various parts of the canoe together.
[src:camakau/camakau] This material is made by cooking the mesocarp of the coconuts in an underground oven, and after several hours of this, beaten.
[src:camakau/camakau] These fibres are then braided to be used for lashing.
[src:camakau/camakau] Rigging rope is made from bark by removing the outer layer of phloem, leaving it to dry, and then twisting the fibres to form a rope.
[src:camakau/camakau] Due to their ability to go at high speeds, carry many people, and survive the harsh conditions of the ocean, David Lewis a Pacific maritime specialist described the camakau as 'the pinnacle of Oceanic canoe technology'.
[src:camakau/camakau] In the canoes built today, the camakau is between 7 and 9 metres in length with a single sail, and the outrigger, the cama, is about 60% of the length of canoe.
[src:camakau/camakau] When sailing the camakau, they are sailed with the outrigger to windward.
[src:camakau/camakau] When they are being sailed upwind, the camakau will change across the eye of the wind, in a manoeuvre called shunting or *cave*.
[src:camakau/camakau] In this manoeuvre of shunting, the steering paddle at the stern is moved to the bow, and the tack of the sail rig is taken to the stern.
[src:camakau/camakau] This allows the outrigger to remain towards the windward side.
[src:camakau/camakau] In the event that the camakau capsizes, the crew drags the craft into shallow water, when able to, and raises the outrigger over the main hull.
[src:camakau/camakau] This corrects the vessel to be able to be sailed again.
[src:camakau/camakau] When offshore, the crew will attempt to sink the outrigger, so that it passes through the water under the canoe, and flips the hull.
[src:camakau/camakau] The camakau is traditionally built by "matai", meaning "carpenters", who came from a carpenter clan.
[src:camakau/camakau] These canoes could only be built by a member of these clans, which were either the "lemaki" or "matai sau" clans.
[src:camakau/camakau] This tradition is not maintained presently, and only the position of head carpenter must be held by a member of one of these clans.
[src:camakau/camakau] The primary role of the head carpenter is to oversee and coordinate the construction and workmen.
[src:camakau/camakau] The labour for the construction of the canoe is primarily carried out by the men, as it is traditionally taboo for women to come into contact with the canoes.
[src:camakau/camakau] The elders perform the tasks which require the most skill, and the youth carry out the more strenuous work such as heavy lifting.
[src:camakau/camakau] Women would normally contribute by weaving mats used to create the sails.
[src:camakau/camakau] There are many culturally significant ceremonies which occur prior to, during and after the construction of the camakau.
[src:camakau/camakau] A (1987), prior to the building of the canoe, those wishing for the construction to occur must present the chief of the island with a "tabua", a sperm whale tooth, this being their official appeal.
[src:camakau/camakau] After this, the chief consults the village elders as to whether it is sensible for this construction to occur, with another "tabua" being presented.
[src:camakau/camakau] Next, the chief carpenter is chosen with the presentation of another sperm whale's tooth to a carpenter by a village elder.
[src:camakau/camakau] Further, throughout the construction process, seven feasts occur.
[src:camakau/camakau] The first occurs when the head carpenter is chosen.
[src:camakau/camakau] The other six feasts occur throughout construction at various stages of completion.
[src:camakau/camakau] M (1929), a race is held when the canoe is first set afloat in which young men race towards village girls who are holding poles with bark cloth.
[src:camakau/camakau] The first to catch a fleeing girl gets all the prizes he is able to hold, with the remaining prizes being divided between the carpenters.
[src:camakau/camakau] Currently, there is an original, traditional camakau in the Fiji Museum.
